oracle.ateam.sample.mobile.v2.persistence.manager

Class AbstractRemotePersistenceManager

  • java.lang.Object
    • oracle.ateam.sample.mobile.v2.persistence.manager.AbstractPersistenceManager
      • oracle.ateam.sample.mobile.v2.persistence.manager.AbstractRemotePersistenceManager
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    PersistenceManager, RemotePersistenceManager
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    DataControlPersistenceManager, RestPersistenceManager

    public abstract class AbstractRemotePersistenceManager
extends AbstractPersistenceManager
implements RemotePersistenceManager
    Abstract class that provides generic implementation of some of the methods of the RemotePersistenceManager interface that can be used by concrete subclasses.

      • createOrUpdateEntityInstance

        protected <E extends Entity> E createOrUpdateEntityInstance(java.lang.Class entityClass,
                                                            java.util.List<BindParamInfo> bindParamInfos,
                                                            E currentEntity)
        Create an entity instance from a list of bind param infos (which are really attribute infos). If an entity instance with the same key already exists in the entity cache, this existing instance is updated and returned. If no such instance is found, and the currentEntity passed is not null, it implies that the primary key of the current entity is changed. In that case, the currentEntity is updated with the new primary key, and the row with old key is removed from SQLite DB, and the cache is updated with the new key pointing to the currentEntity instance.
        Parameters:
        entityClass -
        bindParamInfos -
        currentEntity - - the entity instantiated from DataSynchAction JSON created b serializing the original entity. This is NOT the same instance as in the entity list!!!
        Returns:

      • handleWebServiceInvocationError

        protected void handleWebServiceInvocationError(ClassMappingDescriptor descriptor,
                                               java.lang.Exception e,
                                               boolean rethrow)
        The way web service invocation errors are handled depends on the <show-web-service-invocation-errors> flag in the persistenceMapping.xml file for the specified decriptor. If this flag is true, the error message will be shown to the user. In a production environment, you typically don't want to show such errors to a user, however, during testing it is convenient to directly see the reason why a web service call failed. If the rethrow flag is set to true, the exception will be rethrown, which is used for write actions which should be registered as a pending data sync action when they fail.
        Parameters:
        descriptor -
        e -
